\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12721239 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1460185\charrsid8601884 But you were doing bus driving during the second world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13512717 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1460185\charrsid8601884 Yes. We couldn't go anywhere else, we were tied.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12721239 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1460185\charrsid8601884 Did you retire in 1960?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13512717 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1460185\charrsid8601884 No. I was getting sick of driving. I was on N
ewcastle to London. Aye. And I was getting sick of it. I fought a long time to get on and then when I got on I did it for a number of years and - and I was beginning to get - of course I was sixty then. And I thought, well - why not look for something - b
e
cause there was no pension or anything attached to the United job or anything, see I had nothing to lose that way. The only thing, that I - I was in insurance, that if you paid - I was paying ninepence a week when I first started. They used to pay two and
 
ninepence the company did. But if I was dismissed for misconduct they used to keep the policy and all my ninepences. But if I left on me own accord I could get back what I paid in. It - it - it - really it was a canny thing. And I could get a pound a week
 
for life or a hundred and fifty pounds. Well I had this - I knew that was the only thing I could lose like. But - I don't know whether you would know - the ups and downs like of United, it was just the - just the - the change of life that was how it was, 
y
ou know how things are changing. When I start there they give you a cap and a coat. A dust coat as we called them. That was your uniform. Well - I've always been used to an open necked shirt and - midsummer I went in an open necked shirt and I had to go a
n
